Demographic Changes

Karolina DM

Discussion

This is a report about demographic changes in the world since 1960 to 2019.

Fertility Rate (total, births per woman) is:

rate represents the number of children that would be born to a woman if she were to live to the end of her childbearing years and bear children in accordance with age-specific fertility rates of the specified year.

(source of definition & data: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.TFRT.IN)

The country with the highest fertility rate in 2019 is Niger. The fertility rate is 6.8.

The country with the lowest fertility rate in 2019 is Korea, Rep.. The fertility rate is 0.9.

This is the list of countries with the highest fertility rate (ordered by highest to lowest). Table shows fertility rate difference declining from 1960 to 2019.

Country Fertility Rate drop since 1960 to 2019
Congo, Dem. Rep. -0.2 births per woman
Estonia -0.3 births per woman
Latvia -0.3 births per woman
Czech Republic -0.4 births per woman
Gabon -0.5 births per woman
Sweden -0.5 births per woman
Hungary -0.5 births per woman
Romania -0.6 births per woman
Chad -0.6 births per woman
Niger -0.6 births per woman

This map shows fertility rate in 2019.

The country of EU with the highest fertility rate in 2019 is France. The fertility rate is 1.9. The high fertility rate in France is the result of counting a combined result with dependent territories in the whole world (e.g. French Guiana).

The country of EU with the lowest fertility rate in 2019 is Malta. The fertility rate is 1.1.

This map shows fertility rate in EU countries in 2019.

This chart shows fertility rate in EU countries in 2019.

Death Rate (crude, per 1000 people) indicates:

the number of deaths occurring during the year, per 1,000 population estimated at midyear. Subtracting the crude death rate from the crude birth rate provides the rate of natural increase, which is equal to the rate of population change in the absence of migration.

(data & definition source: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.CDRT.IN)

The country with the highest death rate in 2019 is Bulgaria. The death rate is 15.5.

The country with the lowest death rate in 2019 is Qatar. The death rate is 1.2.

This is the list of countries with the highest death rate (ordered by highest to lowest). Table shows death rate difference declining from 1960 to 2019.

Country Death Rate increase since 1960 to 2019
Bulgaria 7.4 crude (per 1000 people)
Ukraine 6.0 crude (per 1000 people)
Lithuania 5.9 crude (per 1000 people)
Russian Federation 5.0 crude (per 1000 people)
Romania 4.7 crude (per 1000 people)
Latvia 4.5 crude (per 1000 people)
Greece 4.4 crude (per 1000 people)
Japan 3.5 crude (per 1000 people)
Central Europe and the Baltics 3.3 crude (per 1000 people)
Poland 3.2 crude (per 1000 people)

This map show death rate in 2019.

Birth Rate (crude, per 1000 people) is:

Crude birth rate indicates the number of live births occurring during the year, per 1,000 population estimated at midyear. Subtracting the crude death rate from the crude birth rate provides the rate of natural increase, which is equal to the rate of population change in the absence of migration.

(data & definition source: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.CBRT.IN)

The country with the highest birth rate in 2019 is Niger. The birth rate is 45.6.

The country with the lowest birth rate in 2019 is Korea, Rep.. The birth rate is 5.9.

This is the list of countries with the highest birth rate (ordered by highest to lowest). Table shows birth rate difference declining from 1960 to 2019.

Country Birth Rate drop since 1960 to 2019
Gabon -1.5 crude (per 1000 people)
Sweden -2.6 crude (per 1000 people)
Czech Republic -2.9 crude (per 1000 people)
Chad -4.1 crude (per 1000 people)
Hungary -5.2 crude (per 1000 people)
Luxembourg -6.0 crude (per 1000 people)
Congo, Dem. Rep. -6.0 crude (per 1000 people)
Somalia -6.0 crude (per 1000 people)
Estonia -6.1 crude (per 1000 people)
Denmark -6.1 crude (per 1000 people)

This map show birth rate in 2019.

Life expectancy at birth (total, years):

indicates the number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life.

(data & definition source: https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.DYN.LE00.IN)

The country with the highest life expectancy in 2019 is Hong Kong SAR, China. The life expectancy rate is 85.1.

The country with the lowest life expectancy in 2019 is Central African Republic. The life expectatancy is 53.3.

This is the list of countries with the largest life expectancy gains from 1960 to 2019
